<dl id="n22081e"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n22" href="#n22081e">N22 (VI.B.17)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n22all.htm#n22081e"> 81(e)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> twofold truth <small>Blue</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n22081e"><li>FW 490.16 </li><li><a href="../../flex/rA/lexrA.htm#n22081e">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/rA/l39rA.htm#n22081e">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n22081e">MS BL 47484a-259</ms> </li><li>JJA 58:335 <a name="rAd8" href="../../ff/fdra/rda.htm#rAd8">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/rA/rAd8.htm#n22081e">Draft: III&sect;3A.8</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">The mere fact of his having left his order was not enough, nor his refusal to return to it, nor were his heretical opinions&mdash;defended as they might be, and as Aristotle&apos;s own teaching had to be defended in the Church, by the subterfuge of the twofold truth. <small> J. Lewis McIntyre, <a name="BRUNO" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#BRUNO"><cite title="source">Giordano Bruno</cite></a> (1903) 97</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
